<treatment id="03A7A56D6758414CB6BC6E610C99FD8B" LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:03A7A56D6758414CB6BC6E610C99FD8B" httpUri="http://treatment.plazi.org/id/03A7A56D6758414CB6BC6E610C99FD8B" lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="39" pageId="9" pageNumber="38">
<paragraph id="8BB1147B6758414FB6BC6E610DE7F93A" blockId="9.[151,691,1640,1666]" box="[151,691,1640,1666]" pageId="9" pageNumber="38">
<heading id="D0F9A3176758414FB6BC6E610DE7F93A" bold="true" box="[151,691,1640,1666]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="9" pageNumber="38" reason="1">
<emphasis id="B97AC8696758414FB6BC6E610DE7F93A" bold="true" box="[151,691,1640,1666]" pageId="9" pageNumber="38">
Miranda-Ribeiro´s 
<taxonomicName id="4C0E6FF86758414FB7A16E610DFCF93A" authorityName="Miranda Ribeiro" authorityYear="1903" box="[394,680,1640,1666]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Serranidae" genus="Anthias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="9" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="duplicidentatus">
<emphasis id="B97AC8696758414FB7A16E610DFCF93A" bold="true" box="[394,680,1640,1666]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="38">Anthias duplicidentatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
:
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB1147B6758414FB6BC6EBB0E85F80C" blockId="9.[151,1436,1714,1972]" pageId="9" pageNumber="38">
When we started to work with the shallow-water population, our first impression was that it could be an undescribed species, but the color and the apparently much smaller eye lead us to conclude that we were dealing with Miranda-Ribeiro´s 
<taxonomicName id="4C0E6FF86758414FB43C6EF60C64F8A0" authorityName="Miranda Ribeiro" authorityYear="1903" box="[535,816,1791,1816]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Serranidae" genus="Anthias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="9" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="duplicidentatus">
<emphasis id="B97AC8696758414FB43C6EF60C64F8A0" box="[535,816,1791,1816]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="38">Anthias duplicidentatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="133508FE6758414FB56A6EF60CDAF8A1" box="[833,910,1791,1817]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="10.[151,258,1608,1632]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,619,1584]" captionTargetId="figure-265@10.[151,1436,619,1584]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 8. The main reason for Miranda-Ribeiro´s name for the shallow-water morph: duplicidentatus, “doubletoothed”." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5321746" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5321746/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="38">FIG. 8</figureCitation>
). This species was described from the same locality where we first photographed the shallow-water morph (Ilha Rasa, Rio de Janeiro) and even though the data are scarce and the 
<typeStatus id="54B5AAD96758414FB7816F450D44F8DE" box="[426,528,1868,1894]" pageId="9" pageNumber="38">holotype</typeStatus>
missing, the picture of it in Miranda-Ribeiro´s work is remarkably similar to ours´. Years ago, 
<taxonomicName id="4C0E6FF86758414FB7476F7A0DDFF834" authorityName="Miranda Ribeiro" authorityYear="1903" box="[364,651,1907,1932]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Serranidae" genus="Anthias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="9" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="duplicidentatus">
<emphasis id="B97AC8696758414FB7476F7A0DDFF834" box="[364,651,1907,1932]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="38">Anthias duplicidentatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was placed in the synonymy of 
<taxonomicName id="4C0E6FF86758414FB23C6F7A0B8CF834" baseAuthorityName="Guichenot" baseAuthorityYear="1868" box="[1047,1240,1907,1932]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Serranidae" genus="Pronotogrammus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="9" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="martinicensis">
<emphasis id="B97AC8696758414FB23C6F7A0B8CF834" box="[1047,1240,1907,1932]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="38">P. martinicensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation id="EF9F698A6758414FB3236F7A0E0BF80C" author="Anderson &amp; Heemstra" firstAuthor="Anderson" pageId="9" pageNumber="38" pagination="72 - 87" refId="ref6577" refString="Anderson, W. D., Jr., &amp; Heemstra, P. C. (1980) Two New Species of Western Atlantic Anthias (Pisces: Serranidae), Redescription of A. asperilinguis and Review of Holanthias martinicensis. Copeia, 1, 72 - 87." type="journal article" year="1980">Anderson &amp; Heemstra (1980)</bibRefCitation>
, because:
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB1147B675B414CB6EE68910DC4FE9D" blockId="10.[151,1436,152,294]" pageId="10" pageNumber="39">
1. Of the absence of a type to examine, Miranda-Ribeiro’s 
<typeStatus id="54B5AAD9675B414CB55E68910C88FF0A" box="[885,988,152,178]" pageId="10" pageNumber="39">holotype</typeStatus>
was apparently lost. 2. Of the four anthiine species known to occur in Brazilian waters, three could be eliminated from consideration; the only species fitting the original description of 
<taxonomicName id="4C0E6FF8675B414CB58A68EC0BE8FF46" authorityName="Miranda Ribeiro" authorityYear="1903" box="[929,1212,229,254]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Serranidae" genus="Anthias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="10" pageNumber="39" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="duplicidentatus">
<emphasis id="B97AC869675B414CB58A68EC0BE8FF46" box="[929,1212,229,254]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="39">Anthias duplicidentatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<collectingRegion id="49CADA99675B414CB2E768EC0A67FF47" box="[1228,1331,229,255]" country="Venezuela" name="Miranda" pageId="10" pageNumber="39">Miranda</collectingRegion>
Ribeiro, 1903) was 
<emphasis id="B97AC869675B414CB73C69050DC4FE9D" box="[279,656,268,293]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="39">
<taxonomicName id="4C0E6FF8675B414CB73C69050DD9FE9D" baseAuthorityName="Guichenot" baseAuthorityYear="1868" box="[279,653,268,293]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Serranidae" genus="Pronotogrammus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="10" pageNumber="39" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="martinicensis">Pronotogrammus martinicensis</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB1147B675B414CB6ED69500C99FD8B" blockId="10.[151,1436,345,564]" pageId="10" pageNumber="39">
Thus, we agree with Anderson &amp; Heemstra in their assertion. Only after their study was published did the shallow-water morph turn up in the MZUSP collection. If a shallow-water specimen had been available at the time Anderson &amp; Heemstra wrote their paper, it would have cast doubts on their synonymy and, at least, have been noted as a different morph, if not redescribed under Miranda-Ribeiro´s specific name. Moura (2003) followed Anderson &amp; Heemstra and identified MZUSP 47132, the only specimen of the shallow-water morph ever deposited in a Zoological Museum until now, as 
<emphasis id="B97AC869675B414CB5206A130C99FD8B" box="[779,973,538,563]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="39">
<taxonomicName id="4C0E6FF8675B414CB5206A130C9DFD8B" baseAuthorityName="Guichenot" baseAuthorityYear="1868" box="[779,969,538,563]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Serranidae" genus="Pronotogrammus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="10" pageNumber="39" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="martinicensis">P. martinicensis</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
